PS Server Shutdown Verification Script
----------------------------------------
PowerShell utility for validating and confirming successful shutdown of multiple Windows servers after a planned outage or maintenance activity.


Overview
----------
The PS Server Shutdown Verification Script helps administrators quickly verify whether a group of servers has successfully powered off following a shutdown operation.
The script reads a list of server names from a text file, tests network connectivity to each system, and reports whether the server is still reachable or has become unreachable, indicating that the shutdown was likely successful.
This tool is especially useful after bulk shutdown activities, maintenance windows, migrations, or data center operations where administrators need rapid confirmation that systems have powered down as expected.

Features
--------
✅ Simple graphical file picker for server list selection
✅ Bulk verification of multiple servers
✅ Automatic connectivity testing using ICMP ping
✅ Identifies servers that appear successfully powered off
✅ Highlights servers that remain online
✅ Generates a clear summary of shutdown status
✅ Lightweight and easy to run from any administrative workstation

Prerequisites
---------------
Before running the script, ensure the following:
Administrator Access
Administrative privileges are recommended for consistent network testing.
Network Connectivity
The workstation running the script must be able to:

Resolve server names through DNS
Send ICMP echo requests (Ping)
Reach the network segments hosting the target servers

Firewall Configuration
ICMP traffic should be allowed on the target systems for accurate verification.

Server List Format
Create a text file containing one server name per line.
Example:
Plain TextSERVER01SERVER02SERVER03SERVER04SERVER05Show more lines
Save the file as:
Plain TextServers.txtShow more lines

How It Works
---------------
Step 1 – Select Server List
When the script launches, a file selection window appears.
Choose the text file containing the target server names.

Step 2 – Shutdown Verification
The script performs a connectivity test against each server.
If a server responds:
Plain TextSERVER01 is still reachable, shutdown may not have completed.Show more lines
If a server does not respond:
Plain TextSERVER02 is unreachable, shutdown confirmed.``Show more lines
Servers determined to be unreachable are added to the powered-off list.

Step 3 – Review Results
After all servers are checked, the script displays a summary.
Example:
Plain TextPowered Off Servers:SERVER02SERVER03SERVER04Show more lines

